  {
   "kind": 2,
   "value": "(* --- Asymptotic solve: orders 1/u, 1/u^2, 1/u^3 fix 5 of the 7 unknown t-coefficients ---\n   Sum_j (-1)^j Binomial[4,j] j^m = 0 for m=0..3, so subleading Q-data can't enter until 1/u^4;\n   the 4 Q-branches share the same t[a] but have distinct leading powers p_k, so each power of\n   p must vanish separately. This pins a[1],a[2],b[1],c[2],b[3] in terms of S,P,theta and b[2];\n   only b[2] and d[2] survive -- they ARE the two Casimirs Cas2, Cas4. *)\nser3 = Expand@Normal@Series[Bax[Q]/Q[u] /. Q[u_] -> u^p /. (u + x_)^y_ -> u^y (1 + x/u)^y, {u, Infinity, 3}];\nasympEqs = Flatten[Table[CoefficientList[Coefficient[ser3, u, -mo], p], {mo, 1, 3}]];\nasympSol = First@Solve[Thread[asympEqs == 0], {a[1], a[2], b[1], c[2], b[3]}];\nColumn[asympSol]",
   "languageId": "wolfram",
   "outputs": [
    {
     "items": [
      {
